# [JMAP](../wg/jmap.html)

## Summary

The JMAP Working Group met at IETF 126 to discuss progress on CALEXT and JMAP specifications. The CALEXT portion of the session focused on stabilizing the JSCalendar and JSContact specifications, updating vCard 4.0 (`vCard 4.0-bis`), and developing cryptographic extensions. The JMAP portion reviewed updates on mail sharing, object metadata, enhanced result references, email push notifications, blob management, file nodes, and JMAP S/MIME. Plan schedules for several working group drafts were updated, and calls for adoption for new work items were proposed.

---

## Key Discussion Points

### CALEXT Session

#### JSCalendar
* **Presentation:** [jscalendar](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-jmap-jscalendar-00) by Robert Stepanek.
* **Status:** Ready for publication/already in Working Group Last Call (WGLC). Drafts include JSCalendar BIS, JSCalendar iCalendar, and a set of mapping iCalendar updates.
* **Technical Details:** Recent updates include clarifying recurrence rule interpretations, reintroducing the `sent by` property, adding rescheduling compatibility restrictions, and removing null values (except in patch objects) to ease integration with JMAP Calendars.
* **Discussion:** Neil Jenkins noted that JMAP Calendars is currently held at AUTH48 pending these JSCalendar changes. A short (1-2 week) WGLC will be executed for all four documents concurrently once Neil Jenkins publishes the updated JMAP Calendars draft.

#### JSContact
* **Presentation:** [jscontact](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-jmap-jscontact-00) by Robert Stepanek.
* **Status:** JSContact UID draft (bumping JSContact to version 2.0 by making the UID optional) was published. JSContact Profiles is currently in the RFC Editor queue.
* **RFC 9555-bis:** Aligns conversion idioms between vCard/JSContact and iCalendar/JSCalendar. The team is experimenting with JSON pointers for localization, which should be finalized in a few weeks. Publication of RFC 9555-bis will be held to align with the vCard 4.0-bis timeline.
* **Deployment Feedback:**
  * *Addresses:* Splitting street addresses into names and numbers has proven problematic because CLDR lacks address rendering rules to determine field ordering. A temporary workaround is to use only the `name` field. Bron Gondwana suggested utilizing the IETF's liaison with ISO to review how ISO handles street address separation.
  * *Social Profiles:* Apple's undocumented `x-social-profile` has led to semantic inconsistencies. Implementations are currently falling back to custom x-properties.
  * *vCard 4:* It remains virtually nonexistent in the wild; vCard 3 is still the dominant format.
  * *Cryptographic Keys:* Phillip Hallam-Baker is drafting improvements to support native JSON Web Keys (JWKs) instead of wrapping keys in data URIs.

#### vCard 4.0-bis Update
* **Presentation:** [vCard 4.0-bis update](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-jmap-vcard-40-bis-update-00) by Rick Signes.
* **Technical Updates:** Rick Signes addressed 33 errata. 
  * *Commas in URIs:* Commas will only be escaped in non-URI (text and structured text) fields to resolve conflicting escaping specifications.
  * *Group Cards (Member Property):* To refer to text-based UIDs from v3/v4 cards, the `member` property will support a text value type, accompanied by simple comparison rules.
  * *`text/directory` Media Type:* It was deprecated in RFC 6350 but is still used by LDAP. Murray Kucherawy noted that the LDAP community should be consulted via their active mailing list.
* **Next Steps:** Rick Signes plans to merge specific vCard 4 extensions (e.g., JSContact compatibility from RFC 9554 and parameter value encoding from RFC 6868) directly into core vCard 4.0-bis.

#### Cryptographic Extensions
* **Presentation:** [Cryptographic Extensions](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-jmap-cryptographic-extensions-00) by Phillip Hallam-Baker.
* **Technical Details:** The draft was synchronized with running code. To natively support JWKs, the `uri` property in the crypto key object type will be made optional. This breaking change was favored by both Phillip Hallam-Baker and Robert Stepanek over bifurcating the object types.
* **Other Changes:** The class `updates` was renamed to `updateSource` to clarify its purpose. The author is evaluating HTTP polling and UDP DNS lookup mechanisms to fetch contact updates.

