### JMAP Session

#### JMAP Object Metadata, Enhanced Result References, and Mail Sharing
* **Presentation:** [JMAP Object Metadata, Enhanced Result References and Mail Sharing presentation](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-jmap-jmap-object-metadata-enhanced-result-references-and-mail-sharing-presentation-00) by Mauro Stettler.
* **JMAP Mail Sharing ([draft-ietf-jmap-mail-sharing](https://datatracker.ietf.org/authors/draft-ietf-jmap-mail-sharing)):** Introduces sharing capability and required properties to make a mailbox shareable in JMAP for email. It is implemented in Stalwart and is ready for WGLC.
* **JMAP Object Metadata ([draft-ietf-jmap-metadata](https://datatracker.ietf.org/authors/draft-ietf-jmap-metadata)):** Allows public/private metadata to be attached to any JMAP object. The design was simplified in version -02 by removing the separate metadata object and using direct `metadata` and `private-metadata` properties on JMAP objects. It establishes an IANA registry for metadata namespaces.
* **JMAP Enhanced Result References ([draft-ietf-jmap-refplus](https://datatracker.ietf.org/authors/draft-ietf-jmap-refplus)):** Adds JSON Path support to JMAP result references to allow complex query chaining and minimize round trips.
  * *Discussion:* Arnt Gulbrandsen questioned whether it simplifies error handling or introduces atomicity. Mauro Stettler and Neil Jenkins clarified that it is purely for round-trip reduction and does not alter error handling or atomicity. Alexey Melnikov voiced concerns regarding JSON Path query complexity and memory consumption on servers, though the extension remains optional.

#### JMAP Email Delivery Push Notifications
* **Discussion of [draft-ietf-jmap-emailpush](https://datatracker.ietf.org/authors/draft-ietf-jmap-emailpush):** Neil Jenkins reported they are awaiting further implementation experience but expect to run a WGLC before the next IETF meeting. Mauro Stettler has implemented it and noted a design question regarding the bundling of multiple email push payloads to avoid breaking previous push definitions. Neil Jenkins agreed to review past discussions on this issue.

#### Bron's Presentations (Blob Management, File Node, History, and Conditional Updates)
* **Presentation:** [jmap-bron-slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-jmap-jmap-bron-slides-00) by Bron Gondwana.
* **Conditional Changes (Proposed):** Introduces an `ifUnchangedBy` patch check to let clients confirm that properties they care about (e.g., email `seen` status or file contents) have not modified before committing updates, reducing conflicts in high-churn datasets.
* **Object History (Proposed):** Allows querying revision history and deleted objects using a list of objects with timestamps and replacements. Mauro Stettler remarked that this could be beneficial for collaborative editing.
* **JMAP Blob Management ([draft-ietf-jmap-blobext](https://datatracker.ietf.org/authors/draft-ietf-jmap-blobext)):** Replaces RFC 9404 with a structured `blob/set` capability. Supports slicing, concatenation, compression, and diffing.
* **JMAP File Storage Extension ([draft-ietf-jmap-filenode](https://datatracker.ietf.org/authors/draft-ietf-jmap-filenode)):** Integrates metadata and thumbnails (via `draft-ietf-jmap-blobext`).
  * *Discussion:* Arnt Gulbrandsen noted that matching S3 capabilities is sufficient for cloud storage demands. Ben raised questions about random-access reads and writes when mounting JMAP file systems locally. Bron Gondwana confirmed that `draft-ietf-jmap-blobext`'s range operations allow block updates in a single round-trip using inline `blob/set`. Ben requested additional documentation and examples for these use cases.
  * Bron Gondwana discussed handling advisory locks and POSIX atomic swap renames. Introducing an "all-or-nothing" flag to JMAP `set` might be needed to guarantee swap rename atomicity.

#### JMAP S/MIME
* **Presentation:** [jmap-smime](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-jmap-jmap-smime-00) by Alexey Melnikov.
* **Technical Options:** Investigating a simple model (sign, encrypt, or both) versus a complex model (flexible array of nested operations supporting compression, triple wrapping, and header protection). To prevent Denial of Service (DoS) attacks, the complex model would limit chains to three or four operations.
* **Discussion:** Bron Gondwana proposed basing the conversion commands on `draft-ietf-jmap-blobext` as a `blob/set` convert operation. Alexey Melnikov expressed interest but noted potential complexity. Alexey Melnikov will publish the complex option as a new draft to solicit wider feedback.

#### Future Work Discussion
* **Personal Notes:** Hans-Jörg Happel inquired about native JMAP support for personal notes. Rick Signes suggested that using plain HTML/Markdown files in a restricted JMAP file storage account is more robust than creating a specialized note data type. Ben agreed, emphasizing the need for an application-specific "hidden" folder mechanism in `draft-ietf-jmap-filenode` to keep system files out of user-facing file browsers.
* **Tasks:** Hans-Jörg Happel asked about JMAP Tasks. Rick Signes noted that while JSCalendar models tasks (VTODO), a minimal JMAP API for tasks is still required to manage task lists.
* **Server Settings:** Mauro Stettler presented a mechanism implemented in Stalwart for managing account-level properties (e.g., language, timezone, encryption at rest). Bron Gondwana urged Mauro to document this as a draft.

